<br>
I'm not reviewing the story just going over some grammatical and style points. <br>
<br>
The Good: <br>
Your characters speech is suitably individualistic and brings out the best in your writing. Although you tend to overplay it a little too much; delicate touches of slang should be enough to keep your characters individual. <br>
<br>
You character descriptions are also well done if a little like lists at times. You should drop some physical mannerisms into your prose if you can. <br>
<br>
The Bad:<br>
<br>
Spelling. Grrrrrgh. No excuses for bad-spelling. The occasional one I can live with but at least use a spell-checker – mine picked up several straight away.  Use a dictionary.<br>
<br>
The tense of the piece changes in the middle of paragraphs. You are switching from what has happened to what is happening very quickly. Good prose tends to be written in the present tense. <br>
<br>
Repetition of words is bad. Don’t start a sentence in a paragraph with a word you’ve used to start another sentence in the same paragraph. Repeating the same word in a sentence is also a no-no. <br>
<br>
The second chapter has far too much dialogue. See below for a solution to that. <br>
<br>
You are skipping through the story as though it is an outline.  Describe the areas and slow down the pace of the piece.  The first three paragraphs would warrant a single chapter. Lengthen it and take your time. Wallow in the description of the trees, the tangible smell of the brewery and sprawling buildings of the city. Draw your readers in with description. Show don’t tell. <br>
<br>
Although you do an admirable job of describing Sal’s background you don’t convey the drive of his character. Is it fear of something or does he hate the village?  Does he want to be rich or does he seek knowledge?<br>
<br>
You should look at the tone of your piece. Keeping it chatty is nice and easy and allows the reader to get it quickly; but it’s not usually the best way because you are keeping the reader at a distance.  You need to let them into the story not tell them it. <br>
